  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world. It involves the process of making large amounts of money generated by criminal activity, such as drug trafficking or terrorist funding, appear to be legally obtained. This is typically done by funneling the money through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions to disguise its origins. \n\nIn the United States, for example, money laundering is a federal crime that can lead to significant fines and imprisonment. The specific laws and penalties vary by jurisdiction, but the underlying principle is the same: it is illegal to conceal the origins of illegally obtained money. Additionally, many countries have anti-money laundering (AML) regulations and international agreements in place to combat this practice.",
